## Pomponius Mela  

**Pomponius Mela** (born in the late 1st century BC, died around AD 45) was a Roman geographer and the earliest known writer of a systematic description of the known world in Latin. His short treatise *De situ orbis libri III* (“On the Situation of the World”) survived in manuscript form until the late‑15th century and was one of the few classical geographical works that continued to be read well into the Renaissance. Although the work is brief—occupying less than one hundred pages of printed text—it enjoyed a remarkable afterlife, influencing scholars from Strabo to the editors of the first printed editions of the 1470s. The *Encyclopædia Britannica* (1911) characterised it as “dry in style and deficient in method, but of pure [Latinity](/Latinity), and occasionally relieved by pleasing word‑pictures.” [1]  

### Biography  

Little concrete evidence survives about Mela’s personal life. He was probably born at the coastal town of **Tingentera** (modern‑day **[Algeciras]**), a small settlement in the province of Hispania Baetica that later became the Roman colony **[Iulia Traducta]**.[3] The exact year of his birth is uncertain, but internal references to the reign of the emperor Claudius place his activity around AD 43, shortly after the Roman conquest of Britain.[3]  

Mela’s family background appears to have been provincial aristocratic. Several ancient sources suggest a possible connection to the Seneca family: it has been conjectured that he might have been related to Marcus Annaeus Mela, the brother of the philosopher Seneca the Elder and the father of the poet Lucan.[4][5][6][7] If true, this would place him among a network of educated Italic families that migrated from Spain to Rome, a pattern shared by many contemporary writers such as the poets Martial, Lucan, and Quintilian, and the emperors Trajan, Hadrian, and Septimius Severus.[4]  

The little biographical detail that survives is largely derived from later ancient testimonia and from the occasional allusions within his own text. What is clear is that Mela was a Roman citizen who received a typical elite education, was fluent in Latin, and was familiar with the geographic conventions of the Greek tradition that preceded him.[3]  

### Geographical knowledge  

Mela’s *De situ orbis* follows the classical Greek model of dividing the world into zones, but he also introduces some original concepts that reflect the limits of Roman knowledge about the far north and east. He adopts the five‑zone model of the Earth, asserting that only the two temperate zones are habitable, while the intervening torrid zone is too hot for human life; in the southern habitable zone he posits the existence of **antichthones**, a race living in a region inaccessible to those in the northern temperate zone.[13]  

His descriptions of the divisions between **Europe**, **Asia**, and **Africa** echo the work of **Eratosthenes**, though he does not appear to have read **Strabo** directly.[10][11] Mela agrees with the Greek tradition that the **Caspian Sea** is an inlet of the northern ocean, linking it to the Persian and Arabian gulfs, a view shared by most classical geographers except **Ptolemy**.[18][19]  

In the western half of the known world, Mela’s knowledge is comparatively more accurate than that of his Greek predecessors. He provides a relatively precise outline of the Iberian Peninsula’s coastline, the **Bay of Biscay**, and the **British Isles**, and he is the first author to name the **Orkney Islands** ([Orkney_Islands]) with a definition that, while brief, is geographically coherent.[15] His account of the northern seas introduces the term *Codanus sinus* for a large bay north of Germany, mentioning an island called *Codanovia*; this name later appears in **Pliny the Elder**’s writings as *Scatinavia*, a possible early Latin rendering of the Proto‑Germanic *Skaðinawio*, the ancestral term for **Scandinavia**.[14][20]  

Mela’s treatment of the eastern lands is less refined. He places **India** in the southeastern corner of Asia, following **Eratosthenes**, and describes its coast as curving northward toward Scythia before turning westward to the Caspian Sea.[12] He also mentions the **Riphean Mountains** and the mythical **Hyperboreans** near the **Scythian** Ocean, echoing earlier Greek cosmologies.[13][21]  

Overall, his geography blends the best available Roman observations—particularly those derived from maritime reports—with inherited Greek assumptions, resulting in a work that is both a product of its time and a bridge to later medieval and Renaissance cartography.[22]  

### Descriptive method  

Mela’s approach to describing the world follows the tradition of the **periplus**, a literary genre that recorded the observations of sailors and traders as they navigated coastlines. He begins his narrative at the **Straits of Gibraltar**, then proceeds along the southern rim of the **[Mediterranean]** Sea, moves eastward through **Syria** and **Asia Minor**, reaches the **[Black Sea]**, and finally returns to Spain via the northern shores of the **Euxine** and **Propontis**.[23] After covering the Mediterranean islands, he turns to the oceanic **littoral**, describing its coasts in the four cardinal directions—west, north, east, and south—starting again from Spain and Gaul, sweeping around to **India**, then to **Persia**, **Arabia**, and **Ethiopia**, before completing the circuit back to the Iberian Peninsula.[24]  

Unlike many of his Greek predecessors, Mela conceives of **Africa** as a continent wholly surrounded by sea and extending only modestly toward the south, a view that reflects the limited Roman knowledge of the African interior.[25] His method is therefore essentially coast‑wise, relying on the reports of navigators and traders rather than on speculative inland exploration.[26]  

### Editions  

The textual transmission of *De situ orbis* began with the **editio princeps** printed in **Milan** in 1471, the first printed edition of the work.[27] A more critically edited version appeared in 1518, produced by **Joachim Vadian** in **Wien**, which superseded earlier printed attempts.[28] Subsequent scholarly editions followed, including those by **Johann Heinrich Voss** (1658), **Johann Friedrich Gronovius** (1685 and 1696), **A. Gronovius** (1722 and 1728), and finally Tzschucke’s multi‑part edition (1806–1807) in Leipzig, the most elaborate of all.[29]  

A notable English translation was produced by **Arthur Golding** in 1585, celebrated for its literary quality and for making Mela’s ideas accessible to Renaissance scholars.[30] In more recent times, a modern English translation by **F. E. Romer** was published in 1998, offering a revised scholarly commentary and updated notes.[31]  

The work also appeared in multilingual contexts, such as the 1557 Italian edition *I tre libri di Pomponio Mela del sito, forma, e misura del mondo* printed in Venice by Gabriele Giolito de Ferrari.[32]  

